*** Registers
    - As for the 16 8-bit registers We can just make an array of u8s 16 element long
    - V \[u8, 16\];
    - now the most important thing, to access any one register I think syntax was V\[x\].
      so if I want to set VA to contain 0x3F, we can do this 

      V\[0xA\] = 0x3F

      This will set the 10th register to store 0x3F(63)

    - The address register needs to be 16bit as I wrote yesterday only 12 bits are actually needed.
      I researched a bit on why can I not just use a 12 bit uint instead of a 16 bit, it seems efficient at first.
      but ofcourse there is a reason,
      They probably tried to make a 12 bit register, but ran into an glaring issue, since 12 bits is not divisible by 8
      and our standard registers are 16 bits, each memory location is 8 bit or 1 byte,
      on a hardware level it needs complex logic to read 1.5 bytes(12 bits) for each adderess.
    - the solution was simple just use a standard 16 bit register for this. We are going to do the same.
      
      I u16;

    - The Program counter and stack pointers are also considered registers, defined as follows
      
      PC u16;
      SP u16;

